definition.value: Any antibiotic antifungal agent used to treat fungal infections in humans or animals.
Any antibiotic antifungal agent that has been used as a fungicide.

A naphthalenesulfonic acid that is naphthalene-1,3-disulfonic acid carrying additional hydroxy and (naphthalen-1-yl)diazenylsubstituents at positions 7 and 8 respectively. The disodium salt is the biological stain 'acid red 44'.
An organosulfonate oxoanion resulting from the removal of a proton from both of the sulfo groups of 7-hydroxy-8-[(naphthalen-1-yl)diazenyl]naphthalene-1,3-disulfonic acid.
An organoiodine compound that is the ring opened tautomer of fluorescein substituted at positions 2, 4, 5 and 7 by iodo groups.
A benzoate obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy and phenol groups of erythrosin.
A methyl-branched fatty acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate functions of (R)-2-hydroxy-4-methylpentanoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A monounsaturated fatty acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate functions of 4-methylpent-2-enoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A C50 carotenoid that is an intermediate in the biosynthesis of bacterioruberin, a red-coloured pigment found in several Halobacterium and Haloarcula species.
A C50 carotenoid that is an intermediate in the biosynthesis of bacterioruberin, a red-coloured pigment found in several Halobacterium and Haloarcula species.
A member of the class of butan-4-olides that is 3-methylidenebutan-4-olide carrying an additional hydroxy substituent at position 4 (the 4R-enantiomer)

A 6-O-acyl-D-glucose in which the 6-acyl group is specified as (3S)-3,4-dihydroxy-2-methylidenebutanoyl. A secondary metabolite with potent antibacterial activity, occurring specifically in tulip anthers.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of 5-epi-valiolone 7-phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
A TDP-sugar having beta-L-rhamnose as the sugar component.
An organonitrogen compound that contains an amino group that is attached to a carbon which is itself attached to an olefinic carbon and which has been used as an antifungal drug.
Any member of the class of benzofurans which has been used as an antifungal drug.
A TDP-sugar having actinospectose as the sugar component.

A member of the class of isoquinolines that is (3S)-2-L-alanyl-1,2,3,4-tetrahydroisoquinoline-3-carboxylic acid in which the alpha-amino group of the alanyl residue has been substituted by a 1-ethoxycarbonyl-4-phenylbutan-2-yl group (the all-S isomer). A prodrug for quinaprilat (by hydrolysis of the ethyl ester to the corresponding carboxylic acid), it is used as an angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor (ACE inhibitor) used (generally as the hydrochloride salt) for the treatment of hypertension and congestive heart failure.
Any pyridone which is substituted on the nitrogen by a hydroxy group and which has been used as an antifungal drug.
An O-(S-acylpantetheine-4'-phosphoryl)serine(1-) residue in which the S-acyl group is specified as L-2-amino-6-adipoyl
A member of the class of morpholines that has significant antifungal properties.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the triphosphate OH groups of 7-methyl-GTP; major species at pH 7.3.
Any morpholine antifungal agent used as a fungicide.
Any morpholine antifungal agent used to treat fungal infections in humans or animals.
An acyl-CoA(4-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of 3-trans-caffeoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
An acyl-CoA(4-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of hydrocaffeoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A fatty alcohol that is decan-1-ol in which one of the hydrogens at position 9 has been replaced by a methyl group.
A steroidal acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 3-oxochol-4-en-24-oic acid.

A hydrochloride resulting from the reaction of equimolar amounts of quinapril and hydrogen chloride. A prodrug for quinaprilat hydrochloride (by hydrolysis of the ethyl ester to the corresponding carboxylic acid), it is used as an angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor (ACE inhibitor) for the treatment of hypertension and congestive heart failure.
A steroidal acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 3-oxochola-4,22-dien-24-oic acid.
A steroidal acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 3-oxocholesta-4,24-dien-26-oic acid.
An N-acylglycine in which the acyl group is specified as myristoyl (tetradecanoyl).
An enamide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of (Z)-11-methyldodec-2-enoic acid with the amino group of cyclopropylamine.
An N-sulfonylcarboxamide that is (Z)-11-methyldodec-2-enamide in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen is replaced by a methanesulfonyl (mesyl) group.
A hydroxamic acid resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of (Z)-11-methyldodec-2-enoic acid with the nitrogen of hydroxylamine.
An alpha,beta-unsaturated monocarboxylic acid that is cis-2-pentadecenoic acid in which one of the hydrogens at position 14 has been replaced by a methyl group.

An alpha,beta-unsaturated monocarboxylic acid that is tetradecanoic acid (myristic acid) which has undergone formal dehydrogenation to introduce a double bond with Z configuration between positions 2 and 3.
An alpha,beta-unsaturated monocarboxylic acid that is cis-2-tetradecenoic acid in which one of the hydrogens at position 13 has been replaced by a methyl group.
An N-acylpiperidine resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of (Z)-11-methyldodec-2-enoic acid with the amino group of piperidine.
A saturated fatty aldehyde resulting from the formal oxidation of the hydroxy group of 9-methyldecan-1-ol to the corresponding aldehyde.
An enoate ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 11-methyldodec-2-enoic acid with the hydroxy group of ethanol.
A long-chain fatty acid ethyl ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of dodec-2-enoic acid with the hydroxy group of ethanol.
An alpha,beta-unsaturated monocarboxylic acid that is trans-dodec-2-enoic acid in which one of the hydrogens at position 11 has been replaced by a methyl group.
A fatty amide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of (Z)-dodec-2-enoic acid with the amino group of pyrrolidine.
A fatty amide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of (Z)-dodec-2-enoic acid with the nitrogen of piperidine.
An enamide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of (Z)-dodec-2-enoic acid with the amino group of cyclopropylamine.
A fatty amide resulting from the formal condensation of (Z)-dodec-2-enoic acid with the nitrogen of morpholine.
A monocarboxylic acid amide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of (2E)-2-cyano-3-[4-hydroxy-3,5-di(propan-2-yl)phenyl]prop-2-enoic acid with the amino group of 3-phenylpropylamine.
A member of the class of oxindoles that is 5-chlorooxindole in which the two hydrogens at position 3 are replaced by a (3,5-dimethylpyrrol-2-yl)methylidene group.
